<br>
=============================================<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Nuclear Rockets: Past, Present and Future</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The late 1950's and early 1960's were a boom (no pun intended) to nuclear rocket research with such programs as NERVA, ROVER and the infamous Project Orion.  Great strides were made to attempt to expand the human presence in space with a more powerful successor to the chemical rocket.  Nuclear thermal rockets such as NERVA held the promise of doubling the performance of the best chemical rocket with the first generation prototypes.  Project Orion would have been a quantum leap over any other existing or foreseeable propulsion system.  Unfortunately federal budget cutbacks of the early 1970's killed all nuclear powered propulsion research.  As many as 600 NASA employess were let go with the closing of the Plum Brook station near Sandusky, Ohio and from the Lewis Research Center in Cleveland.<br>
<br>
The next 30 years would become a dark age for nuclear propulsion research.  With the media hyped 3 Mile Island nuclear power plant accident the word 'nuclear' became a public relations nightmare.  <br>
<br>
That brings us to the present.  With the current U.S. administration's policy, nuclear power (and nuclear propulsion research) is in a renaissance period.  One billion dollars is to be spent over the next 5 years on nuclear power in space.  Great things may yet happen in the 'conquest of space'.<br>
<br>
How fast can a nuclear powered spaceship go? Even the most dedicated 'couch potato' is moving along at 100,000 kilometers per hour for that is about the orbital speed of the Earth.  Unfortunately most of us are stuck to the Earth as it goes about it's annual trek.  The same applies to the compromise that is the International Space Station and the Space Shuttle as they are dragged along by the Earth.  We are all going around in circles mighty fast and getting nowhere.  Because of their high cost/low performance chemical rockets are prohibitively expensive for manned missions beyond the Moon.  The best case chemical rocket mission would take around six months from Earth to Mars.  The same trip could be made in eight weeks with a nuclear propulsion system.   Some nuclear propulsion designs are theoritically capable of speeds near 10% that of light (100 million kilometers per hour).  Nuclear power and propulsion are necessary if humanity ever intends to explore and colonize the solar system in the foreseeable future.  There is no known alternative that provides as much bang for the buck.<br>
=============================================<br>
